    {
        "content": "<p>The idea behind <code>prod_mem</code> is that you already have a submonoid</p>",
        "id": 450825862,
        "sender_full_name": "Eric Wieser",
        "timestamp": 1720737284
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Note that in your theorem , you can combine <code>ht1</code> and <code>ht</code> to build a submonoid to use the approach I described</p>",
        "id": 450825978,
        "sender_full_name": "Eric Wieser",
        "timestamp": 1720737313
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>But otherwise, the trick you're missing is <code>induction s using Finset.cons_induction</code></p>",
        "id": 450826013,
        "sender_full_name": "Eric Wieser",
        "timestamp": 1720737332
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>yes. but it means that, to apply the existing  <code>prod_mem</code>, one would have to declare a <code>Submonoid</code> if it has not been done. Is this so intended? or maybe it would be nice to have the other version in mathlib as well?</p>\n<p>thanks for the suggestion, I will try!</p>",
        "id": 450826904,
        "sender_full_name": "Yoh Tanimoto",
        "timestamp": 1720737626
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>You always have the option of building the submonoid in the middle of the proof with a <code>let</code></p>",
        "id": 450828685,
        "sender_full_name": "Eric Wieser",
        "timestamp": 1720738150
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>oh I see.<br>\nin the case of <code>unitInterval</code> (in <a href=\"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/pull/12266\">#12266</a>), what should I do, should I use <code>let</code> or leave the definition in, say, <code>Mathlib/Topology/UnitInterval</code>?</p>",
        "id": 450829424,
        "sender_full_name": "Yoh Tanimoto",
        "timestamp": 1720738360
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The latter</p>",
        "id": 450830889,
        "sender_full_name": "Eric Wieser",
        "timestamp": 1720738835
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>ok, thanks!</p>",
